\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line According to the evaluator\'2C Criteria 1\'2C 2\'2C 4\'2C 5\'2C and 6 are in need of improvement. It should be noted that Milpark Business School \'28MBS\'29 currently offers the Advanced Diploma in Management \'28NQF level 6\'29 which it intends phasing out\'2C and replacing it with the proposed Advanced Certificate in Management at NQF level 6.\line \line The evaluator stated that the programme is aligned with the requirements of the HEQF\'2C with respect to NQF levels and credits.  However\'2C an evaluation of the course outline of the 8 instructional offerings \'285 core and 3 electives\'2C from which a student must choose one\'29 indicates that for some modules\'2C like Workplace Relations and Global Corporate Citizenship\'2C the disciplinary content and theoretical depth is inadequate in relation to the number of credits \'2820\'29 assigned. With respect to the module entitled Integrated Business Strategy the syllabus omits some important aspects pertaining to business strategy\'2C but instead includes aspects pertaining to research and academic writing. The evaluator thought that the academic integrity of the programme would be enhanced if the module entitled Global Corporate Citizenship is replaced by a module in Economics\'2C as managers need a good knowledge and understanding of micro- and macro-economic concepts and principles\'3B given the impact of economic factors on the organization and its influence on decisions made by managers in the organization. \line \line No textbooks are prescribed for the modules in the programmes\'3B instead\'2C the Institution submitted a \'E2\'80\'9CBook\'2FReading List\'E2\'80\'9D\'2C with an average of three books per module.  With respect to the module entitled Global Corporate Citizenship\'2C no books were identified\'2C and all of the reading material was to be sourced from resources prepared by the United Nations.\line Work-integrated learning is not a part of the curriculum\'2C although the programme is targeted primarily at those in full-time employment.  \line \line The evaluator furthermore indicated that the admission requirements reflected in the draft brochure\'2Fprospectus are incorrect\'2C for a student needs to have passed an NQF 5 qualification \'28Higher Certificate or equivalent\'29 before being accepted for the 120-credit Advanced Certificate in Management\'2C which is pegged at NQF 6. \line \line According to the information submitted by Milpark Business School it appears that the institution possesses a cohort of suitably qualified and experienced academic staff members to offer the programme via distance learning.  On average\'2C the academic staff members identified to \'E2\'80\'9Cteach\'E2\'80\'9D on the programme have nine years\'27 tertiary teaching experience.\line \line According to the submission by MBS the range of teaching and learning methods to be employed for the distance Advanced Certificate in Management consists primarily of independent self-study.  Additional academic support will be delivered via specially-prepared DVDs\'2C and via one of three levels of online support.  The evaluator also indicated that the institution places a high premium on student retention\'2C throughput and graduation rates\'2C and to this end\'2C it ensures that at-risks students are identified early\'2C and timeous interventions are made to assist them to succeed in their studies.\line \line Student assessment policies and procedures are well-structured\'2C and meet the minimum standards in terms of assessment in a higher education environment.  Policy guidelines\'2C inter alia\'2C inform the appointment and role of examiners and moderators\'2C promotion criteria\'2C the conducting of examinations\'2C and student appeals.  Procedures are documented to receive\'2C mark and record formative assessment tasks within a time-frame that allows students to benefit from feedback.  The moderation process is clearly articulated.  However\'2C the number of formative assessments for all of the modules is inadequate.  Apart from self-evaluation exercises\'2Ftests\'2C it is recommended that a minimum of two formative assessments should be compulsory for each module in the programme\'2C thereby offering students an opportunity to improve their year mark after receiving detailed and constructive feedback on their first formative assessment.  Furthermore\'2C the weighting allocated to the assignment \'2830\'25\'29 should be decreased to take into consideration the fact that the assignments are completed under non-examination conditions\'2C and some students may \'E2\'80\'9Coutsource\'E2\'80\'9D the completion of the assignment\'2C or get undue assistance in completing the assignment. \line \line The Directorate supports the recommendation that the programme should be accredited with conditions.\line \cell \pard 

